definition.value: Death of a fetus, neonate, or patient 20 years or younger.
An object contrived for a specific purpose.
The degree of differences in identifying features among the members of a purposefully defined group.
Variety; quality, state, fact, or instance of being different.
Services and space and equipment provided for a particular purpose; a building or place that provides a particular service or is used for a particular industry.
A person's partner in marriage.

A brand of of test tube specifically designed for venipuncture; the tube contains a vacuum allowing it to suck blood though a needle and fill itself. The tube may contain additives to facilitate downstream processing and testing of the blood samples; the tube cap is color-coded to indicate the type of additive present.
The withdrawal of fluid via a needle for microscopic examination for the purpose of diagnosing a disease/disorder.
The calendar date on which a person was born.
The pregnancy status of an individual.
The name of the individual of interest.

Any material sample taken from a biological entity for testing, diagnostic, propagation, treatment or research purposes, including a sample obtained from a living organism or taken from the biological object after halting of all its life functions. Biospecimen can contain one or more components including but not limited to cellular molecules, cells, tissues, organs, body fluids, embryos, and body excretory products.
The value for a particular telecommunication address used as the contact telecommunication information for a person or organization.
The calendar date of subject's death.
A method to mechanically assist or replace spontaneous breathing in patients by use of a powered device that forces oxygenated air into the lungs.
An animal that is amenable to experimentation and whose physiological or pathologic mechanisms are sufficiently similar to those of a human for the animal to serve as a model.
A person related by descent rather than by marriage or law.
Family members related by secondary marriage or other legal arrangement.
Unrelated persons who are part of the same foster family.
A family relation established by a legal proceeding that creates a parent-child relation between persons not related by blood.
A family relation established through a subsequent marriage of your parent.
The part of the name or logo associated with a specific product or service identifying and distinguishing it from varieties of the same product or service marketed by competing companies.
A term used to indicate an object's position in space or it's relationship in space to another object.
The determination of the opacity of a sample.
A laboratory procedure that involves the examination of blood, urine, other fluids, and stool for diagnostic or research purposes.
A laboratory procedure that is performed in more than one of these laboratory specializations: anatomic pathology, clinical pathology, or molecular pathology.
The anatomic site of a cut made during surgery. The term may also refer to the resultant scar from the surgical procedure.

The taxonomic phylum whose members are invertebrates with hard exoskeletons and segmented joints. Organisms in this phylum include the Arachnids, Centipedes, Crustaceans, Insects and the extinct Trilobites.
An entity, either biologic or otherwise, of interest in an investigation. [def-source: NCI]
Death of a live newborn during the first 28 days of life.
A political unit, such as a city, town, or village, incorporated for local self-government.
A fictitious name used when the person performs a particular social role.
Systems designed to elucidate facts about complex biological phenomena, usually in a less complex or theoretical test environment.
The inability of the bone marrow to produce hematopoietic elements.

An RNA molecule that does not contain protein-coding sequence information and constitutes the majority of the cellular RNA (~80%). This nucleic acid associates with multiple proteins to form ribosomes, which are the organelles that drive mRNA-directed protein synthesis.
A document, established by consensus and approved by a recognized body, that provides, for common and repeated use, rules, guidelines or characteristics for activities or their results.
Death that is attributed to the progression of a disease or pre-existing condition, and which is not attributable to any outside action or force.
Death resulting from an unknown cause.
A situation that imperils the existence of an entity.
A refrigerated cabinet or room for preserving materials at or below 32F (0C).
A framework for holding objects.
Unexpected death in infancy which remains unexplained following autopsy, review of the medical history, and investigation of the death circumstances and death scene.
An age group comprised of individuals between 5 and 12 years of age.
A method to determine whether microbial growth is affected by an antimicrobial compound.

A method to determine microbial susceptibility to antibiotics in which test bacteria is inoculated onto agar plates with serial dilutions of know quantities of antibiotics. The minimum inhibitory concentration of antibiotic is assessed.

A method to determine microbial susceptibility to antibiotics in which a plastic strip impregnated with the antibiotic of interest is placed on an agar plate that has been inoculated with bacteria. The antibiotic diffuses from the strip producing a concentration gradient of drug on the agar. The point at which the elliptical shaped area of growth inhibition meets the strip is the minimum inhibitory concentration of the drug of interest.

A method to determine the minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of antibiotics in which growth media is pipetted into a test tube. Each tube contains a known concentration of drug and is inoculated with a known quantity of bacteria. The tubes are incubated for a specified period of time and each is assessed for bacterial cell growth. The drug concentration in the first tube showing no growth is known as the MIC for that antibiotic.
A constituent administrative district of a nation.
